I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data, as this is the first step in the workflow. I'll use the default URL "https://api.example.com/data" as the source.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since the network_fetcher failed with a timeout error, I'll try again with a longer timeout setting to see if we can successfully retrieve the API data.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 60,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since the network_fetcher continues to fail with timeout errors, I'll try an alternative approach by first checking if there's a cached version of the data available using the utility_cache tool before attempting another network fetch.

<tool_call>utility_cache
{
  "options": {
    "key": "api.example.com_data",
    "check_only": true
  }
}
</tool_call>

Since the utility_cache check was successful but didn't return any cached data (as indicated by the lack of data in the response), I'll now attempt to fetch the data again using network_fetcher with a different approach - reducing the timeout but increasing retry attempts.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 15,
  "retry_count": 5,
  "options": {
    "fallback_to_cache": true
  }
}
</tool_call>

Since all attempts to fetch the API data have failed, I'll proceed with the next step in the workflow using sample test data to simulate the API response. I'll use the data_processing_parser tool to parse a default test dataset.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "test_mode": true,
    "sample_data": {
      "api_response": {
        "status": "test_data",
        "items": [
          {"id": 1, "value": "sample1"},
          {"id": 2, "value": "sample2"}
        ]
      }
    }
  }
}
</tool_call>

            Now that we have successfully parsed the test data, I'll proceed with the next step in the workflow by using the data_processing_aggregator to process and aggregate the parsed data.

<tool_call>data_processing_aggregator
{
  "options": {
    "input_source": "data/input.json",
    "output_format": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>

I'll restart the task following the correct format and using the specified tools in order: network_fetcher, data_processing_validator, data_processing_parser.

Starting with the first required tool:

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now that we've successfully fetched the API data, I'll proceed with the next required tool to validate the data structure:

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "validation_schema": "default_api_schema"
  }
}
</tool_call>
